Question #1
markdown:
>>Based on the reading, which of the following statements are true? || Select all that apply.<<

[ ] The size estimates of the additive manufacturing industry includes revenue earned from equipment sales, services provided, and an estimate of the value added by new parts and products produced using AM.
[ ] Additive manufacturing equipment is not yet ready (inasmuch as it is either too slow or too expensive to operate) to produce consumer goods.
[x] Additive manufacturing creates new possibilities for product design, retail, and the customer experience.

[explanation]
The size estimates of the AM industry include equipment sales and services yet do not calculate the value-added by parts produced by AM. Cost-modeling in a way which captures AM-produced value is challenging, as you will learn in Week 6, and an industry-wide analysis would be impossible. 

The article mentions several instances of AM being used for consumer goods.
[/explanation]

name: Question #4
markdown:
>>According to the article, which of the following are reasons the industrial community is exploring the use of AM?|| Select all that apply.<<

[ ] AM processes exploit a wider range of metallic materials than are possible to be processed with conventional methods
[x] Additive manufacturing creates possibilities for on-demand production and the conversion of physical inventory to digital models
[x] Additive manufacturing can produce high-detail prototype models more quickly and with less manual effort than conventional methods
[ ] Additive manufacturing processes eliminate the need for suppliers and a supply chain

[explanation]
The article does not mention AM materials. Likewise, though the article describes the ability of AM to affect supply chain dynamics, it does not state that it will eliminate the need for suppliers. This is further not a reasonable inference to make, as AM consumes materials and products still will require distribution (either distributed or centralized) and packaging.
[/explanation]

name: The AM Workflow (from CAD to part)
The Additive Manufacturing Technology Spectrum (15 min)
Question #1
markdown:
>>What are the four attributes referenced in the video that can be used to benchmark the performance of a manufacturing process?<<

( ) Rate, Quality, Repeatability, Speed
( ) Cost, Volume, Quality, Flexibility
(X) Rate, Cost, Quality, Flexibility
( ) Materials, Rate, Repeatability, Volume

[explanation]
The answer comes directly from the video. However, we can exclude some characteristics based on their names.

Repeatability is a synonym for quality in one regard (quality of parts is tied to a process which can make them reliably) and moreover all qualified manufacturing processes must be repeatable to be deployed. Speed is also a synoynym for rate.

Volume is ambiguous and could be defined as spatial area (which would then imply flexibility) or as quantity (which is a direct produt of rate).

Likewise, materials can be considered a subset of flexibility (a process which can manipulate more materials is inherently more flexible in the objects it can produce).
[/explanation]

name: Question #3
markdown:
>>Which of the below explanations best justifies the high cost for small unit quantities of injection molded (IM) parts?<<

( ) The feedstock material used in injection molding is more expensive than the feedstock used in the AM processes.
(x) The injection molded part must take into account the cost of machined tooling for producing the parts, even to produce only one part.
( ) The design process for the injection molded part is much more time consuming than for the AM parts.

[explanation]
Injection molding is a high-throughput inexpensive process that is used to make thousands of products you interact with daily. It is unlikely that the material is more expensive than specialized filament for AM. Likewise, it is unlikely that the cost of the design process for the injection molded part is much more expensive than that of AM. Both processes are producing the same part, and these numbers were queried from a service bureau which receives the design before estimaing the cost. Finally, although an IM design must include a tool design, this extra effort is (either partially or totally) offset by the increased design effort required for AM inasmuch as the industry is relatively unfamiliar with AM compared to its mastery of injection molding acquired over the course of many decades.

The only difference (among these answers) is tooling, which is required for injection molding yet not necessary for AM.
[/explanation]

Question #1
markdown: >>Which of the below statements best describes the relationship between extrusion AM when compared to conventional polymer forming (e.g., injection molding)?<< ( ) The modulus and strength of extrusion AM parts are comparable to that of conventionally manufactured parts ( ) Extrusion AM, without post-processing can reliably achieve surface finish comparable to conventionally manufactured parts (X) The strength of extrusion AM parts is typically less than conventionally manufactured parts, in at least one direction relative to the printed layers ( ) Unlike injection molding which can be adapted to process metal-filled polymer feedstocks, extrusion AM cannot work with metal-filled polymers [explanation] The strength of extrusion AM parts is typically less than that of conventionally manufactured parts because of the weak interlayer bonding compared to conventional manufacturing process such injection molding which results in monolithic parts. [explanation]

name: Question #3
markdown: >>Which of the following statements about extrusion additive manufacturing is true?<< ( ) Extrusion AM results in parts with anisotropic mechanical properties ( ) The strength of printed parts is highly correlated to layer thickness and infill density ( ) With decreasing layer thickness, surface quality improves considerably (x) All of the above [explanation] All of the above statements are true about extrusion AM. Strength of the parts in the plane of printing is higher compared to strength of the parts perpendicular to the build direction due to weak interlayer bonding. [explanation]

name: Question #4
markdown:
>>The commonly used feedstocks for desktop extrusion AM systems are in the form of:<<

(x) Filaments with standardized diameter 
( ) Pellets
( ) Rods
( ) All of the above

[explanation]
Spools of thermoplastic filament are a convenient format for the relatively low build volumes of desktop extrusion AM systems. For meter-scale and above build areas, it becomes more economical to supply thermoplastic feedstock in the form of pellets.
[explanation]

name: Question #5
markdown: >>Extrusion additive manufacturing is one of the most versatile additive processes, which lends it to a wide variety of applications. What application is not a common commercial use of extrusion AM?<< ( ) Jigs and fixtures (x) High-precision bearings ( ) Prototype housings ( ) Tooling [explanation] The line-by-line and layer-by-layer nature of extrusion AM by necessity introduces many interfaces and weld lines into the completed part. This reduces surface quality overall and gives rise to a stair-stepping effect along curved surfaces. As a result, extrusion AM is not capable of producing the high-quality surfaces necessary for high-precision bearings without significant post processing. [explanation]

name: Question #1
markdown: >>Which of the following statements are true when comparing photopolymerization AM to extrusion AM? ||Select all that apply.<< [x] Photopolymerization involves a chemical reaction [x] Photopolymerization uses liquid feedstock [ ] Only photopolymerization can be used to process polymer parts [x] The feedstock material in photopolymerization printers is fused at a lower temperatures than the feedstock in extrusion printers [explanation] Photopolymerization is involves crosslinking of monomers via a chemical reaction, whereas extrusion involves heating and resolidification of thermoplastic. Photopolymers are generally liquid resins, whereas extrusion printers use filaments or pellet feedstock. Finally, the thermosetting reaction is activated by relatively low intensity UV light without any heating required. By contrast, extrusion requires heating the thermoplastic close to its melting temperature. [explanation]

name: Question #2
markdown:
>>Which of the following are typical reasons to choose photopolymerization AM? || Select all that apply.<<

[x] The part requires fine details and smooth surfaces
[ ] The part needs to be recycled by melting after use
[ ] Dissolvable supports are desired

[explanation]
Photopolymerization can be used to produce fine details as the curing spot can be directed with high precision. Since the polymer is a thermoset, it cannot be recycled by melting, and the supports and parts are printed using the same material, and therefore the typical SLA process cannot be used to produce dissolvable supports. 
[explanation]

name: Question #3
markdown:
>>Why do desktop stereolithography (SLA) systems use an inverted configuration?<<

(x) It allows for a shallow resin tank resulting in a compact size
( ) It enables a higher resolution
( ) It allows heavy parts to be printed
( ) It can print significantly faster than large, vat-based SLA systems

[explanation]
Desktop SLA systems use an inverted configuration because it allows for a shallow resin tank that does not need to accommodate the entire part, as the part is progressively raised out of the tank. 
[explanation]

name: Question #4
markdown:
>>What is the energy source used to cause photopolymerization of the resin in a SLA system?<<

( ) An X-ray beam
( ) An infrared lamp
( ) A scanning electron beam 
(x) UV light

[explanation]
Photopolymerization in SLA systems is initiated by UV light.
[explanation]

name: Question #5
markdown:
>>Which of the following are mainstream applications of SLA parts? ||Select all that apply.<<

[x] Dental models
[x] Short-run tooling
[x] High detail presentation models
[x] Fabrication of ceramic components, via printing followed by sintering

[explanation]
SLA is used for all of the above applications due to its fine details, and large materials library. It can also be used for indirect fabrication of ceramics by printing resins with suspended ceramic particles, followed by a sintering process that removes the polymer and fuses the ceramic particles. 
[explanation]

name: Introduction to Powder Bed Fusion AM
Introduction to Powder Bed Fusion AM
Question #1
markdown:
>>The build rate of SLS is slow as compared to alternative polymer AM processes.<<

( ) True
(x) False

[explanation]
SLS is a comparatively fast process as compared to FFF / SLA.  By preheating the powder, material needs relatively little additional energy to achieve melting / fusion.
[explanation]

name: Question #2
markdown:
>>Identify the major components common to SLS and SLM AM systems.<<

[x] Laser
[x] Scanning mirrors
[x] F-theta lens
[x] Recoater
[x] Powder supply
[x] Powder bed

[explanation]
All are correct.  Common components include elements for energy delivery, namely a laser, scanning mirror, f-theta lens, as well as a powder handling system comprising a recoater, powder supply, and powder bed.  
[explanation]

name: Question #3
markdown:
>>Aside from build rate, what other factors make SLS attractive for fabricating polymer parts as compared to FDM or SLA? ||Select all that apply.<<

[x] Parts can be nested in 3D
[x] The parts do not exhibit surface defects from support structure

[explanation]
SLS parts are provided adequate support from the surrounding unfused powder during printing, so support structures are not necessary.  The enables closely packing parts in 3d to more efficiently use the build volume (increases productivity).
[explanation]

name: Question #4
markdown:
>>Post processing of SLM parts often comprises:<<

( ) Heat treatment to reduce residual stress
( ) Support material removal
( ) Surface finishing
(x) All of the above


[explanation]
SLM is among the most post-processing intensive AM processes. Components require support material removal and surface finish improvement by machining, as well as heat treatment to improve mechanical properties.
[explanation]

name: Question #5
markdown:
>>Which of the following factors influence the surface quality of a metal part made by the SLM process? || Select all that apply.<<

[x] Powder particle size
[x] Laser spot size
[x] Layer thickness
[x] Precision of support removal

[explanation]
All are correct.  The combination of powder particle size, laser spot size, and layer thickness all affect the resolution and surface finish of an SLM part. Post processing for support removal is also critical, as this machining operation may improve, though not eliminate, surface roughness.
[explanation]

name: Question #6
markdown:
>>To be compatible with SLM, feedstock must be:||Select all that apply. <<

[x] In powder form
[ ] Steel or aluminum alloys
[x] Capable of withstanding rapid heating and cooling
[ ] Insensitive to oxidation at high temperature

[explanation]
Feedstock must be in powder form for recoating, and be able to survive the rapid heating and cooling inherent to the process.  A wide range of metals may be printed in SLM, including light alloys, steels, superalloys, and refractory metals, in part because oxidation is mitigated by the inert build environment.  However, the material must maintain its properties despite the rapid temperature changes; most castable alloys are also SLM compatible. Many SLM materials are oxidation sensitive, yet this is managed by maintaining an inert build atmosphere.
[/explanation]

name: Question #7
markdown:
>>In SLM, the microstructure (i.e. grain size, texture, and orientation) of the part:||Select all that apply. <<

[x] May vary locally according to the local temperature and cooling rate included by part geometry and process parameters.
[x] May be different according to the material and process parameters selected.
[ ] With present technology, is directly specified as an input parameter in the design software.
[x] Influences the mechanical properties of the part.

[explanation]
Composition and time-temperature history affect the microstructure of SLM components.  The microstructure produced is a function of process parameters, component geometry (e.g. reduced thermal conduction from the melt pool when printing overhanging features), and metallurgical properties of the feedstock.  Critically, microstructure can have a considerable effect on the mechanical properties of a component, thus it would be advantageous to control it during processing.  While possible from a process-control standpoint, it is currently infeasible to model the SLM process with sufficient fidelity to generate the toolpaths and process parameters necessary to control microstructure.
[explanation]

name: Question #8
markdown:
>>Compared to SLS, the high-speed sintering (HSS) and multi-jet fusion (MJF) processes: ||Select all that apply. <<

[ ] Work with metals
[x] Use infrared lamps to fuse the polymer powder
[x] Require inkjet deposition of an infrared absorbing agent prior to fusion
[ ] Scan the infrared lamp along a series of component contours, just like the laser beam in SLS

[explanation]
HSS and MJF use an inkjet head to deposit infrared absorptive pigment where the feedstock is to be fused.  Because the infrared radiation does not need to be precisely directed, several infrared lamps are typically used to irradiate the entire build platform, or a single lamp is swept across it, at a much slower speed (~0.1 m/s versus ~1-10 m/s) than the laser scanning in SLS.  Metals are not compatible with these processing methods, due to the higher temperatures and heat flux required to melt them.
[explanation]

name: Question #1
markdown: >>Which of the following statements (choose one) is true about material jetting additive manufacturing?<< ( ) The strength and modulus of parts made by material jetting are always the same as injection molded parts (x) Multi-color and multi-material parts can be fabricated with a high level of detail ( ) Because individual droplets of material must be ejected from a nozzle, material jetting is not scalable to large parts [Explanation] Material jetting AM is capable of depositing inks of various colors and mechanical properties; therefore, multi-color and multi-material parts can be fabricated with a high level of detail. [Explanation]

name: Question #2
markdown:
>>The resolution of material jetting AM is limited by: <<

( ) The properties of the ink, such as its surface tension and viscosity
( ) The printhead nozzle diameter
( ) The dynamics of landing and spreading of the droplet when it hits the part/substrate
(x) All of the above
( ) None of the above

[Explanation] 
The resolution of material jetting AM is limited by the nozzle diameter and the rheological properties of the ink, which together influence the size of the ejected droplet.  The size of the ejected droplet, and how it spreads upon impact with the substrate, define the resolution of material jetting AM.
[Explanation]

name: Question #3
markdown:
>>What materials can be used in the process of material jetting additive manufacturing? || Select all that apply. <<

[x] Photopolymers
[ ] Fiber-reinforced composites
[X] Nanoparticle inks
[x] Wax

name: Question #4
markdown:
>>Material jetting sometimes involves jetting of polymers immediately followed by UV curing.  As a result, no support material is required for overhangs and arches. <<

( ) True
(x) False

[Explanation] False; as dictated by the part geometry, material jetting AM requires support material during the build.  When the droplet lands on the part, it must have a supporting surface to land upon.  Therefore, it is generally not possible to build even short overhangs without underlying support material.
[Explanation]

name: Question #5
markdown:
>>Consider the use of material jetting to fabricate metal or ceramic parts. Why is it favorable to use metal or ceramic nanoparticles in the ink, rather than liquid metal or ceramic?||Select all the true statements. <<

[ ] Nanoparticles do not form agglomerations like larger particles do
[x] Nanoparticles have a lower sintering onset temperature than larger particles and sinter more rapidly than larger particles
[x] A nanoparticle ink can be jetted at much lower temperature than a molten metal or ceramic
[ ] Nanoparticle inks, per unit volume, are more cost-effective than bulk metals and ceramics


[Explanation] Sintering onset temperature decreases with particle size and nanoparticles tend to sinter more rapidly than larger particles due to smaller diffusion distances. Nanoparticle inks can be jet at lower temperatures than metal or ceramic melting temperatures because the nanoparticles are dispersed in a carrier liquid such as a common solvent.
[Explanation]

name: Question #1
markdown:
>>Which of the following statements are true about binder jetting additive manufacturing?|| Select all that apply. <<

[ ] Parts coming directly from the powder bed generally have high strength
[ ] Binder jetting AM cannot be used to fabricate multi-colored parts
[ ] Because individual droplets of material must be ejected from a nozzle, binder jetting is not scalable to large parts
[x] In the binder jetting workflow, metal parts need to be sintered or infiltrated after printing to give high strength

[Explanation] 
After printing, the powder is held together only by the binder which is not mechanially strong; therefore, as-printed ("green") parts are weak.  As a result, metal parts must be sintered or infiltrated to give high strength.  Binder jetting of multi-colored parts is possible through the use of colored binder.  The scalability of inkjet printing technology allows binder jetting to be scalable to large parts, while maintaining relatively rapid build rates.  Binder jetting of large sand casting molds is a great example of this. [Explanation]

name: Question #2
markdown:
>>The resolution (i.e., smallest feature size and surface roughness) of binder jetting AM is limited by: <<

( ) Powder particle size
( ) Infiltration of the binder into the powder bed
(x) Both
( ) Neither of the above

[Explanation] Both the powder particle size and the interaction of the binder and the powder bed will play a role in defining the resolution of a binder jet part.  The surface roughness will be expressed by the particle diameter, on average.  The spreading of the binder into the powder (influenced by the powder bed density, particle size, droplet size, wettability, and other factors) determines the incremental dimension of the part that is added with each deposited droplet.
[Explanation]

name: Question #3
markdown:
>>Because binder jetting AM utilizes the bonding of the binder to the powder and not direct bonding of powder particles during the build process, binder jet parts do not suffer from residual stresses. <<

(x) True
( ) False


[Explanation] This is true, because large thermal gradients are not applied during the build process, binder jet parts do not suffer from residual stresses.
[Explanation]

name: Question #4
markdown:
>>Which of the following would improve the economics of binder jetting AM?||Select all that apply. <<

[x] Inkjet printhead with higher jetting frequency and/or more nozzles
[x] Binders that cure at room temperature in the print bed
[x] Lower-cost, easily spreadable metal powders
[x] Rapid sintering processes that exhibit minimal distortion during shrinkage

[Explanation] All of the above are correct: Higher frequency and more nozzles would allow faster deposition of fluid, binders that cure at lower temperatures would reduce curing time, easily spreadable and cheaper powders would reduce the cost, and rapid and efficient sintering would result in lower sintering times and higher throughput.
[Explanation]

name: Question #5
markdown:
>>Which of the following are current commercial implementations of binder jetting additive manufacturing? ||Select all that apply. <<

[x] Binding of metal powders followed by infiltraton of a second metal to achieve full density
[x] Binding of metal powders followed by sintering to achieve near full density
[x] Manufacturing of rapidly dissolvable pharmaceutical tablets/pills
[ ] Direct printing of meter-scale metal components, such as ship propellors
[x] Fabrication of sand molds for casting of meter-scale metal components

[explanation]
Binder jetting is currently used to produce metal parts (either followed by sintering or infiltration) and sand molds, but meter-scale metal components are still not commercially viable due to warping and thermal effects during post-processing.
 [/explanation]

name: Introduction to Directed Energy Deposition AM
Introduction to Directed Energy Deposition AM
Question #1
markdown:
>>Which of the following attractive attributes of DED for fabricating metal parts, as compared to powder bed fusion (SLM/EBM)?||Select all that apply.<<

[ ]DED can realize more complex geometries
[x] DED has a higher build rate
[ ] DED achieves better surface finish
[x] DED is capable of changing the composition of the part during the print

[explanation]
DED is faster than SLM/EBM and can change the composition of the part during printing by delivering powders of different composition through the nozzle. It can not make complex geometries or have a better surface finish compared to PBF, because it deposits material more coarsely, and cannot build fine support structures as in powder bed processes. 
[explanation]

name: Question #2
markdown:
>>The build rate of wire feed DED is typically greater than the build rate of powder feed DED.<<

(x) True
( ) False

[explanation]
Wire-feed DED is typically a faster process as compared to powder-feed DED, because a greater volume of material can be fed using a wire.
[explanation]

name: Question #3
markdown:
>>What is the key difference between cold spray and melting-based DED processes?<<

( ) Cold spray can repair damaged parts
(x) Cold spray uses kinetic energy to fuse the material instead of a concentrated heat source
( ) Cold spray always must be operated in an inert atmosphere

[explanation]
Cold spray uses kinetic energy and makes solid state bonds between powder particles. Cold spray does not need an inert atmosphere as the process is accomplished at temperatures far below the melting point of the feedstock. All DED processes can repair damaged parts.
[explanation]

name: Question #4
markdown:
>>Which of the following post-processing steps are typically performed after a part is built on a DED machine? ||Select all that apply.<<

[x] Heat treatment to reduce residual stress
[ ] Sintering
[x] Machining of key surfaces

[explanation]
DED is a near net shape process so it requires machining of dimensionally critical surfaces. It also needs heat treatment to relief residual stress or to improve mechanical properties.
[explanation]

name: Question #5
markdown:
>>Which of the following choices are current types of commercially used DED AM systems? || Select all that apply:<<

[x] Powder feed
[x] Wire feed
[x] Hybrid DED/CNC machines
[x] 5-axis DED machines
[x] DED machines using standard robotic manipulators 

[explanation]
DED systems can be categorized based on their feedstock (powder or wire) as well as relative motion between the substrate and the deposition head. There are also hybrid DED/CNC machines that can alternate between additive and subtractive operations.
[explanation]

name: Question #6
markdown: >>Compared to selective laser melting (SLM), which of the following statements about DED are true?||Select all that apply.<< [x] DED systems typically have a higher power laser [ ] DED systems scan the laser faster than SLM systems [x] DED forms a larger melt pool than SLM [explanation] DED normally uses higher power laser, the laser moves slower (m/min rather than m/s) and this results in deeper melt pool. [explanation]

name: Question #1
markdown:
>>Paper LOM can be applied to casting processes (sand casting, investment casting) because the a LOM part can be used as an expendable pattern.<<

(x) True
( ) False

[explanation]
Because the paper used in paper LOM is easily burned out, it can be effectively used in casting operations.
[explanation]

name: Question #2
markdown:
>>Which of the following are correct attributes of the paper LOM process?  || Select all that apply.<<

[ ] It produces parts with strength comparable to fiber-reinforced thermoplastics
[x] It generally uses easy to handle and low cost feedstocks
[ ] It is ideal for highly intricate designs with overhangs and other small features
[x] It can produce full-color objects

[explanation]
Paper is an easy to use and inexpensive feedstock material, yet does not have the mechanical properties of thermoplastics, especially those reinforced with, e.g. carbon fiber. Because the paper must be cut, finely detailed features, especially thin pillars and overhangs, will likely not form properly. However, LOM can be used with inkjet color deposition to produce photorealistic parts.
[/explanation]

name: Question #3
markdown:
>>For Metal LOM, the polymer powder is typically used to fuse consecutive layer, and therefore requires high temperature and pressure to finalize the bond.<<

( ) True
(x) False

[explanation]
Polymer powder is used in Impossible Objects' composite LOM process, not in metal LOM.
[/explanation]

name: Question #4
markdown:
>>Which of the following are challenges of using LOM? || Select all that apply. <<

[x] It is difficult to remove excess material from within internal features of printed parts.
[ ] It is difficult to procure the raw material feedstocks for the most popular LOM machines.
[ ] Users often need to ensure optimal environmental conditions with respect to humidity and moisture in order to achieve good results in LOM.

[explanation]
It is difficult, or impossible, to remove fully enlosed waste material inside of an internally sealed off cavity in an LOM machine. However, the raw feedstock materials are generally easy to procure and standardized, and because the forming conditions (heat, pressure) are applied locally rather than ambiently the machines are generally insensitive to external environmental conditions.
[/explanation]

name: Question #5
markdown:
>>Select all of the following statements that are correct with regard to LOM processes for fiber-reinforced composites. || Select all that apply. <<

[x] LOM of composites can use woven or non-woven fiber sheets analogous to those used in traditional composite lay-up.
[ ] LOM of composites uses ultrasonic energy to join the consecutive layers.
[ ] LOM machines for composites use 5-axis robotic manipulators to build highly curved, non-planar layers.
[x] An important goal of composite LOM is to achieve mechanical properties comparable to traditional composite layups, yet to digitize the workflow.

[explanation]
LOM of composites uses fiber sheets similar to a composite layup while attemping to digitize the workflow of traditional composites manufacturing, but does not bond them using ultrasonic energy. The sheet feedstock material means that the machines cannot be put on a 5-axis table. 
[/explanation]

name: Question #6
markdown:
>>Which of the following statements accurately describe LOM processes broadly? || Select all that apply.<<

[x] The process in many ways is a form of hybrid manufacturing: a combination of additive and subtractive manufacturing processes.
[x] The z-axis resolution is limited by the feedstock sheet thickness and the effective thickness of any bonding agent between the layers.
[ ] A specific LOM process can only be used with one sheet material; in other words, a part cannot contain sheets of two materials in different layers.
[x] LOM machines use different cutting mechanisms, such as a knife, laser, or milling tool, depending on the material and other details.
[x] LOM does not involve a phase change (e.g., melting or evaporation) of the sheet feedstock.

[explanation]
LOM involves additive manufacturing (sheet by sheet) as well as subtractive (use of a cutting tool, which varies from process to process). The z-axis resolution can not be finer than the thickness of an individual layer plus the margin applied by the bonding agent (if any). However the parts are bonded, the material does not undergo a phase change. 

Many LOM processes use different materials, and this is one of the stronger advantages of LOM versus some other AM processes.
[/explanation]

Question #1
markdown:
>>Which of the following characteristics of additive manufacturing processes guide its application potential?||Select all that apply. <<

[ ] AM can process a wider range of metallic materials than conventional processes and therefore unlock new material capabiltiies
[x] AM can create complex geometries difficult to achieve using conventional method and therefore can reduce cost for complex geometries
[ ] Mass manufacturing capability is a pre-requisite to finding valuable applications of additive manufacturing
[x] AM is more flexible than conventional processes and can therefore unlock new value dimensions, especially in terms of customization and personalization

name: Establishing a Business Case for AM
Establishing a Business Case for AM
Question #1
markdown:
>>Which of the following statements are true regarding the qualitative graphics presented above that compare AM to CM for specific scenarios? || Select all that apply. <<

[ ] AM will never compete with CM for mass production quantities when total value is considered
[x] These comparisons account only for the cost of producing a part, not the value it creates for the end-user
[ ] AM is only cost-competitive with CM when part designs are highly complex (e.g., contain lattice structures)
[x] AM technologies will continue to advance with time, changing the equivalence points in these comparisons

[explanation]
AM may never be as inexpensive as CM for mass production quantities, yet it is not accurate to say it will never compete, as the flexibility and complexity enabled by AM can allow manufacturers unprecedented creativity in the design space that justify this cost premium. Moreover, while  complexity is a major advantage of AM vs CM, you saw from the galley fitting example that neither need be the reason to use AM and some part-for-part comparisons still work out in AM's favor, as well as that speed along can be a compelling driver of AM versus CM for certain categories of parts.

It is true, however, that the figures on this page represent only the cost of producing a part, but do not capture the value created by a new design. And, as was noted at the end, developments across the field are continuing to expand AM's capabilities and potential business case as machines become more efficient and less expensive.
[/explanation]

name: Question #2
markdown:
>>An automotive manufacturer uses AM to directly fabricate customized steering wheel grips, based on scan data acquired from customers at their local dealer. Which of the following value propositions of AM does this best represent?<<

( ) Speed, because the parts must be printed while the customer waits at the dealer
(x) AM cost advantage, as the more complex and personalized versons would be prohibitively expensive using CM
( ) Direct part comparison economics, because the reason for using AM is to reduce material waste
( ) Prototyping, as the best performing models will be put to mass production

[explanation]
For the first two answers, it should be clear that a near-infinitely varied part (as is the case with a customized object that is both designed with customer input and based on their specific biology) will always be significantly greater cost using conventional methods than AM because of the elimination of tooling. The examples previously on this page make clear that the benefits of AM for speed are on the front-end, yet when production has begun CM is more effective in terms of cycle time for many processes than AM.

The third answer, direct economics, can be discarded outright. This is not the case of comparing two copies of the same product, produced differently. Moreover, if it were, it is clear that CM is more effective for simpler geometries at mass volumes.

For the fourth answer, it is clear this is a direct production method not a prototyping instance, although it is possible that if a certain geometry becomes a high-seller the manufacturer may choose to integrate it into their CM product line.
[/explanation]

name: Question #3
markdown:
>>For which of the following scenarios would AM be a good candidate versus a conventional production method?||Select all that apply.<<

[x] Enabling investment casting of fine jewelry designed using an advanced CAD platform
[x] Testing the design of a new animated children's TV show character with small groups of potential viewers, via a physical model
[ ] Production of a large volume of inexpensive, single-use polymer components (e.g. straws or cups)
[x] Fabricating a small quantity of a key component of a larger electromechanical device during an unexpected supplier delay

[explanation]
As you saw in the Art, Design and Architecture module to this section, AM can be used for investment casting of elegant and complex jewelry designs that cannot be produced other ways (or, if they could, would be cost prohibitive due to labor intensivity).

AM is an excellent candidate for producing photorealistic designs for customer testing. AM is not, however, a strong candidate for production of a high-volume of simple parts. 

Because of AM's flexibility (inasmuch as machines, other than those which are qualified to produce production runs of single parts, are non-dedicated to specific products), it is also an excellent candidate for augmenting production capacity during supplier delays.
[/explanation]

Question #1
markdown:
>>What does viscosity of a polymer represent?<<

( ) Resistance to tension
(x) Resistance to shear
( ) Neither
( ) Both

[explanation] Viscosity is the quantity that represents fluids resistance to flow. Mathematically, it's the ratio of shearing stress (F/A) to the velocity gradient. [/explanation]

name: Question #2
markdown: >>Which of the following are true statements about thermoplastics? ||Select all that apply.<< [x] Thermoplastics can be heated and reshaped multiple times without degradation of material [ ] Thermoplastics contain polymer-chains which are cross-linked [x] Thermoplastics exhibit creep and stress relaxation at room temperature [ ] Viscosity of thermoplastics increase with increasing temperature [explanation] In thermoplastics polymer chains are not cross-linked to each other which results in their capability to be re-heated and shaped multiple times without any degradation. And because of their viscoelastic behavior, thermoplastics are particularly susceptible to creep and stress relaxation. [explanation]

name: Question #3
markdown:
>>Select the statement that best describes the viscosity of thermoplastics.<< 

[ ] Dependent on temperature
[ ] Dependent on shear rate
[x] Dependent on both temperature and shear rate
[ ] None of the above

[explanation]
Molten thermoplastics are examples of non-newtonian fluids. Hence their viscosity is dependent on both temperature and shear rate. 
[explanation]

name: Question #5
markdown:
>>Polymer material support combinations require which of the following?<< 

( ) Support structures can either be dissolvable or broken away
( ) Support material should be thermally compatible with build material
( ) High temperature polymer build materials are compatible only with break-away support system
(x) All of the above

[explanation] Support material should not melt when a structural material is being printed over it, which requires that the support material and structural material are thermally compatible. Most of the support materials which dissolve in solvent after print have low melt temperatures and hence are not compatible with high-temperature polymer build materials [/explanation]

name: Question #1
markdown:
>>Which of the following subsystems determine the rate of extrusion AM?<<

( ) Motion system
( ) Extruder/drive mechanism
( ) Liquefier/heater
(x) All of the above

[explanation]
As shown in the above process physics chart, the interaction of these three subsystems establish the performance limits of the machine. The slowest/least capable of these three determines the maximum throughput for the entire system.
[explanation]

name: Question #2
markdown:
>>In order to be sufficiently heated, the polymer cross-section should reach its melt temperature before reaching the converging flow region of the printhead.<<

(x) True
( ) False

[explanation]
If the entire cross-section doesnt reach the melt temperature, then a section of relatively rigid polymer will encounter the converging flow in the nozzle and the force requirement for extrusion will increase dramatically. This usually results in print failure.
[explanation]

name: Question #3
markdown:
>>In order for a specific combination of rate and resolution to be possible, this point must lie on or under all the curves corresponding to the maximum constant velocity, extrusion force, and heat transfer capability of the extrusion AM system in question.<<

(x) True
( ) False

[explanation]
The correct region is the intersection of the area under all three curves (for a given constant velocity, extrusion force, and heat transfer). In other words, all subsystems must be capable of reaching a given performance state for the system as a whole to reach that state.
[explanation]

name: Question #4
markdown:
>>What is the mechanism of failure that limits extruder force?<<

(x) Shear at the filament-drive interface
( ) Torsion of the filament
( ) Softening of the filament due to frictional heating

[explanation]
When the extruder fails, the shear force applied to the filament by the textured extruder wheel is greater than the filament material can withstand, resulting in shear failure of the filament and print failure.
[explanation]

name: Question #5
markdown:
>>What are the practical considerations that limit printhead velocity in gantry-based desktop extrusion systems? ||Select all that apply.<<

[x] Printhead mass
[ ] Mass of printed part
[x] Drive motor specifications
[ ] Print bed temperature

[explanation]
The mass of the printhead attached to the gantry will determine the gantry settling time into each new trajectory (for a given drive motor specification). For a given printhead mass, a higher performing drive motor (as determined by its torque-speed curve and response characteristics) will allow for the printhead to more rapidly follow a given trajectory.
[explanation]

name: Question #6
markdown: >>What effect does a heated build chamber have on residual stresses in the part? ||Select the best answer.<< ( ) Increased residual stresses, due to thermal expansion of the polymer. (x) Decreased residual stresses, because the polymer chains are allowed to creep and relax throughout the build. ( ) Decreased residual stresses, because the interface temperature between each layer has additional thermal energy immediately after deposition. ( ) Increased residual stresses, because interlayer bonding increases, and therefore the part can withstand greater stress during service. [explanation] A heated build volume (heated to some fraction of Tg) increases polymer chain mobility and allows chains to change conformation over time. Immediately after extrusion, chains conformation is on average longer and the entropy due to this extended conformation creates a stress in the material. Elevated temperatures allow the polymer chains to slowly return to a relaxed state, reducing residual stresses in the part. [explanation]

name: Question #1
markdown:
>>Which of the following is true about the effect of orientation on mechanical properties of two parts printed at different orientations?<<

( ) They have the same modulus and strain to failure
( ) They exhibit different modulus and different strain to failure
(x) They exhibit same modulus but different strain to failure
( ) They exhibit neither the same modulus nor different strain to failure

[explanation] Independent of the print orientation, parts printed at different orientations show the same modulus because the defects or weak interlayer adhesion corresponds to strain to failure but not to stiffness. Any specimen printed will have the same modulus, irrespective of the orientation. [/explanation]

name: Question #2
markdown:
>>Mechanical anisotropy of printed parts can be reduced through...?<<

( ) Process parameter optimization
( ) Interface welding
( ) Post-part irradiation
( ) Epoxy infiltration
(X) All of the above

[explanation] Please refer to the section "Mechanical anisotropy of extrusion AM parts" for detailed explanation of all the post-processes available. [/explanation]

name: Question #3
markdown:
>>Interlayer adhesion strength is weak in FDM printed parts due to...?<<

( ) Insufficient diffusion of polymer chains between layers
( ) Limitation of the process to provide sufficient time to heat previous layer
( ) Absence of polymer chain interlinking in thermoplastics
(X) All of the above

[explanation] Interlayer adhesion in extrusion AM is dependent on the diffusion of polymer chains between successive layers, which is in-turn affected by the temperature of successive layers. [/explanation]

name: Question #1
markdown: >>Which of the following statements are true?||Select al that apply.<< [x] Stereolithography involves a chemical reaction to create a 3D solid. [ ] A part produced by SLA can be shaped after printing by embossing. [x] Post-curing is typically required to achieve the final mechanical properties of a printed part. [x] The ductility of an SLA printed part can change over an extended period of use and exposure to ambient light. [explanation] Stereolithography involves a photoinitiated chemical crosslinking reaction to transform a liquid resin to a solid part. The resulting polymer is a thermoset, and therefore cannot be resolidified after heating. Therefore it cannot be hot embossed. Post curing is generally required, and embrittlement can take place over time due to remaining reactants. [explanation]

name: Question #2
markdown:
>>Which of the following factors determines the selection of the light source (i.e., the laser wavelength) in an SLA printer?<<
( ) The resolution required
(x) The optical properties of the photoinitiator
( ) The size of the build platform
( ) The refractive index of the monomer

[explanation]
The wavelength of light has to be matched to the absorption spectrum of the photoinitiator for optimal efficiency. Most photoinitiators are activated by UV or blue light.
[explanation]

name: Question #3
markdown:
>>Which of the following processes occur during post-curing of a part printed by SLA?||Select all that apply.<<
[x] The crosslink density is increased compared to the green state 
[x] The Youngs modulus of the part increases
[ ] The surface roughness of the part is reduced
[ ] The support material is removed

[explanation]
Post curing increases the crosslink density compared with the green part. In general, this results in increasing the stiffness of the part. 
[explanation]

name: Question #4
markdown:
>>Which of the following precautions would be strongly recommended for a mechanical bracket printed by SLA for outdoor use?||Select all that apply.<<
[x] Application of UV-blocking paint after printing and post-curing
[x] Inclusion of light stabilizers in the resin
[ ] Surface smoothing
[ ] None of the above

[explanation]
UV light can result the slow continuation of the crosslinking reaction using residual reactants. Therefore it is essential to apply surface protection and include UV stabilizers.
[explanation]

name: Question #5
markdown:
>>Which of the following are essential differences in the resin chemistry between a part with a high Youngs modulus and an elastomeric one?||Select all that apply<<
[x] The types of bonds and functional groups between the reactive end groups on the monomer
[x]  The crosslink density
[ ] The cure depth
[ ] Resin viscosity
[explanation]
The mechanical properties of the part are determined by the types of bonds and functional groups on the monomer and the crosslink density.  One can think of the crosslinked polymer network as a network of springs: if the network has more, shorter springs is will be stiffer than a network comprising fewer, long springs.  
[explanation]

name: Question #1
markdown:
>>Which of the following factors influence the time required to print a part by SLA?||Select all that apply.<<
[x] Area of each layer
[x] Layer thickness
[x] Recoating speed (i.e., speed of the blade)
[x] Laser spot size

[explanation]
All of the above factors influence the total printing time, because the time of laser scanning is related to the layer area, the spot size (smaller spot size requires more travel distance). The recoat time adds to the time in between layers, and the total print time is inversely proportional to the layer thickness because the laser needs to scan each layer. To some extent, the laser scan speed can be increased within thinner layers, but this doesnt fully overcome the extra time needed to scan additional layers when the layer thickness is reduced.[explanation]

name: Question #2
markdown: >>The finest linewidth that can be achieved using a particular SLA system is defined by ||Select the best answer.<< ( ) The wavelength of the laser source ( ) The focal length of the optics (x) The intensity profile of the laser incident on the surface of the resin ( ) The laser power [explanation] The spot size is defined by intensity profile of the light incident on the surface, because this determines the smallest feature width that can be cured, in combination with the optical properties of the resin. [explanation]

name: Question #3
markdown:
>>What is the cause of shrinkage during photopolymerization?<<
( ) Evaporation of some of the resin
(x) Replacement of van der Waals interactions with covalent bonds, reducing the average molecular distance
( ) Presence of support structures that hold the part onto the build platform
( ) Separation of uncured resin from the cured part
[explanation]
The source of shrinkage at the molecular level is the reduced inter-atomic spacing when a covalent chemical bond is formed, replacing physical bonds. 
[explanation]

name: Question #4
markdown:
>>What strategies can improve isotropy of mechanical properties and reduce stress of parts made by photopolymerization?||Select all that apply.<<
[x] Selecting a layer thickness that is less than the effective depth of cure
[x] Using a scan pattern that allows the residual stress to relax during printing
[ ] Maximizing the laser intensity
[ ] Minimizing the scan speed
[explanation]
Selecting a layer thickness less than the cure depth allows crosslinking between the layers, improving isotropy, while an overlapping scan pattern such as the star-weave ensures the residual stress in the part is minimized. 
[explanation]

name: Question #1
markdown:
>>Polymer powder feedstock can be reused an unlimited number of times in SLS without any influence on the part properties.<<

( ) True
(x) False

[explanation]
Polymers undergo material aging due to the thermal cycling experienced during SLS, altering the melting behavior of the polymer and the resulting mechanical properties of the part. Therefore, recycled polymer powders are mixed with virgin powder for subsequent prints.
[explanation]

name: Question #2
markdown:
>>The most widely used, and suitable type of polymer for SLS is:<<

( ) Amorphous thermoplastic
(x) Semi-crystalline thermoplastic
( ) Photopolymer
( ) Thermoset 

[explanation]
Semi-crystalline thermoplastics. Compared to amorphous thermoplastics, they have a well-defined melting temperature, relatively low melt viscosity, and a thermal hysteresis during melting and cooling that allows for accommodation for material variation. Also, unlike thermosets, they do not require chemical cross-linking.  
[explanation]

name: Question #3
markdown:
>>Adding pigments to the polymer feedstock allows you to change the color of parts, but likely requires alterations to the processing conditions and can change part properties.<<

(x) True
( ) False

[explanation]
Pigments can affect the heat absorption and the laser penetration depth, which changes the degree to which there is inter-layer fusion and part isotropy.
[explanation]

name: Question #4
markdown:
>>Which of the following statements are true when comparing high-speed sintering (HSS) to selective laser sintering (SLS)?  || Select all that apply.<<

[ ] HSS involves both a laser and infrared heat source to controllably melt the powder
[x] HSS heats the polymer much slower than SLS
[x] HSS can better accommodate for material variation, including thermal aging
[ ] HSS requires more uniform powders (i.e., particle diameter and shape)

[explanation]
HSS has much slower heating with an infrared lamp compared to with a laser in SLS, allowing for a longer residence time so that there is more time for the polymer to flow and sinter together - making the process more robust to material variation.  HSS involves infrared heating, but does not use a laser.
[explanation]

name: Question #5
markdown:
>>Shrinkage of a part created in SLS is typically managed by:<<

( ) Heating the powder bed to as close to Tm as possible without exceeding it
( ) Flowing inert gas over the sections heated with the laser to increase solidification rate
( ) Applying mechanical and/or gas pressure to the powder bed during the build to ensure the part retains the same geometry
(x) Holding powder bed slightly above Tg and cooling slowly after the build is completed

[explanation]
The polymer needs to be heated above Tm to fuse the powder particles together. Pressure cannot easily be applied to the build volume because the powders are loose and the top of the build platform is open. To accomodate for shrinkage, the part needs to be cooled slowly and uniformly, so the powder bed is kept at a temperature below Tm but above Tg so that the part solidifies but most of the shrinkage occurs upon cooling the bed after the build is complete. 
[explanation]

name: Question #1
markdown:
>>What are the 3 primary physical phenomena at play in SLM? || Select all that apply.<<

[x] Fluid Dynamics
[x] Radiation Transport
[ ] Doppler Shift
[x] Heat Transfer

[explanation]
Radiation transport describes the heating of feedstock by the laser.  Clearly, this heat is transferred into the powder and previously solidified material, selectively liquefying it.
[explanation]

name: Question #2
markdown:
>>Unfused powder in SLM provides an excellent heat sink.<<

( ) True
(x) False

[explanation]
False. The powder is a poor conductor of heat; most thermal energy is dissipated from the melt pool via conduction through previously solidified material.
[explanation]

name: Question #3
markdown:
>>What is the origin of recoil pressure in SLM?<<

( ) Suboptimal powder bed packing
(x) Material vaporization from the melt pool
( ) Surface tension effects between the melt pool and powder
( ) Thermally induced residual stresses

[explanation]
Recoil pressure is the reaction force arising from material vaporizing off the top of the melt pool.
[explanation]

name: Question #4
markdown:
>>The surface roughness on the underside of an overhanging feature in SLM is excessively rough.  What may be done to improve the outcome? || Select all that apply.<<

[x] Reduce laser power in the area of the defect.
[x] Increase laser scan speed in the area of the defect.
[ ] Reduce laser scan speed in the area of the defect.
[ ] Increase laser scan speed in the area of the defect.
[x] Increase the amount of support material under the defect.
[ ] Change the laser wavelength.

[explanation]
Optimal surface roughness on overhanging features results when sintering of the underlying powder is prevented. Reducing the laser power and increasing the scan speed lower the energy density delivered to the melt pool, which should be just high enough to fully densify the first layer of the overhang.  Increasing the amount of support material provides an alternative mechanism for wicking heat out of the first overhanging layer by providing a low thermal impedance path.
[explanation]

name: Question #1
markdown:
>>A common process map for SLM can easily be constructed for multiple materials by overlaying the the laser power and scan velocity results from experiments without non-dimensionalization of the values.<<

( ) True
(x) False

[explanation]
The process parameters need to be normalized so that results from experiments with different materials can be properly compared. Different materials may require drastically different process parameters (and thus input energy density) to achieve full part density and avoid defects.
[explanation]

name: Question #2
markdown:
>>If all other process parameters are kept constant, the effective energy density felt by the powder during the laser scan is always the same at all positions as the build proceeds.<<

( ) True
(x) False

[explanation]
The material is exposed to different temperature gradients and thermal history depending on the thermal boundary conditions. For example, material at the edge of the part will have a large effective energy density than that towards the middle because the edge of the part borders powder particles, which conduct the heat away much more poorly than the solidified regions towards the center of the part and so the melt pool remains longer.
[explanation]

name: Question #3
markdown:
>>The process window for SLM doesnt extend to mutually high high power and scan velocities because of:<<
( ) Keyhole formation
( ) Overheating
( ) Lack of fusion
(x) Balling
( ) Only the physical limitations of the equipment

[explanation]
Balling occurs when long melt track produced by high energy density is broken up by surface tension, preventing fully dense solidification.  This limits the power and scan velocity that can be used to achieve fully dense parts typically before the physical limits of the machine are reached. Overheating occurs at even higher energy density, when the scan velocity is low but the power is high, resulting in keyhole formation. We also move out of the conduction zone in the process map with too low of an energy density (high scan velocity but low power).
[explanation]

name: Question #4
markdown:
>>Which of the following infill scan strategies results in optimal residual stress management in SLM?<<

( ) Stripe
( ) Meander
(x) Chessboard
( ) Zigzag

[explanation]
The Chessboard scan strategy allows for local control of raster orientation and heat management, but at a cost of lower build speed.  Meander rasters across the whole part without any breaks, which is the fastest but results in the worst thermal control and stress management. The Stripe strategy is faster than Chessboard but with worse thermal control. Zigzag is just a general way of describing the back-and-forth raster movement that is employed for all scanning strategies.
[explanation]

name: Question #5
markdown:
>>Which of the following statements are true with respect to process parameter optimization in SLM? || Select all that apply.<<

(x) An optimal scan algorithm would apply different scan parameters in thick versus thin regions of the part.
( ) Parameters can be optimized without consideration of the hatch spacing, because the metal is not re-melted when the adjacent scan line is traced.
( ) The combination of laser power and scan speed that gives the highest density of solidified metal is roughly the same for aluminum, steel, and tungsten.
( ) Keyhole defects occur when the energy density is too low, and therefore melting of the powder is insufficient.  

[explanation]
Because the effective energy density under a fixed scan pattern varies locally according to the thermal boundary conditions of the part, an optimal scan algorithm would need to change the parameters to maintain the same effective energy density in each region of the part.  Keyhole defects occur when the energy density is too high, rather than too low.  Re-melting typically occurs with the next adjacent scan, and is necessary to achieve full density.  And, the process parameters that give maximum density will vary for each material. 
[explanation]

name: Question #1
markdown:
>>An ink you have developed is creating satellite drops during jetting. By examining the jetting parameters diagram, what action may be taken to alleviate this problem, resulting in well-controlled drops without satellites?<<

( ) Increase the jetting velocity
( ) Increase the nozzle diameter
(x) Combine your ink with an additive to reduce the surface tension of the fluid
( ) Increase the jetting voltage

[explanation]
Looking at the jetting parameters diagram, by reducing the surface tension of the fluid, the Ohnesorge number will increase, thereby moving the operating point closer to the printable fluid region.
[explanation]

name: Question #2
markdown:
>>Thermal inkjet printing is generally compatible with a larger number of ink formulations than piezoelectric inkjet printing.<<
( ) True
(x) False
[explanation]
Because thermal inkjet printing requires vaporization of the fluid to form the pressure pulse for ejection and piezoelectric inkjet printing does not, piezoelectric inkjet printing is compatible with more ink formulations.
[explanation]

name: Question #3
markdown:
>>Stable line formation from overlapping discretely jet droplets is dependent on which of the following attributes? || Select all that apply.<<
[x] Jetting frequency
[x] Droplet diameter
[x] Fluid viscosity
[ ] Surface tension

[explanation]
The interplay between jetting frequency, droplet diameter, and fluid properties are all important in determining the printed pattern.
[explanation]

name: Question #4
markdown:
>>Which of the following issues could result in a fluid being incompatible with jetting? || Select all that apply.<<
[x] The fluid has a high melting point which exceeds the operating temperature of the inkjet printhead.
[x] The fluid contains particles which clog the inkjet nozzle.
[x] The Weber number, calculated based on the maximum fluid velocity that the printhead can create, and other parameters, is a approximately 1. 
[ ] The equilibrium contact angle of the fluid on the substrate is approximately 120o.

[explanation]
The first and second choices would render the fluid incompatible with the inkjet printhead. The third choice means that there is insufficient energy to eject a drop from the nozzle, according to the discussion of the jetting parameter space. The fourth choice refers to the drop-substrate interaction, which is important for the attainment of printed features, but does not influence the jetting operation.
[explanation]

name: Question #5
markdown:
>>The minimum feature size in jetting can be approximated by:<<
(x) The size of the spread/dried droplet on the substrate
( ) The diameter of the nozzle
( ) The diameter of the drop in flight
( ) All of the above
[explanation]
The minimum feature size in material jetting will be best approximated by the size of the spread/dried drop on the substrate, because this represents the final size of the feature. It depends on the impact velocity of the drop, the fluid properties, and the wettability on the substrate.
[explanation]

name: Question #1
markdown:
>>What characteristics of liquid metals make metal jetting more difficult than polymer jetting?|| Select all that apply.<<

[x] Higher required operating temperature
[ ] Higher density of liquid metal
[x] High surface tension
[x] Reactivity with solid surfaces

[explanation]
Because metals generally have a higher melting temperature than polymers, metals are more difficult to jet since the components for the inkjet must sustain higher temperatures. Additionally, reactivity of metals with the printing environment (e.g., oxidation) make jetting of metals more difficult than jetting of polymers.  Last, the high surface tension of metals requires a greater pressure to eject droplets.
[explanation]

name: Question #2
markdown:
>>AM of metal parts using the deposition mechanism of jetting is possible through the use of:||Select all that apply.<<
[ ] Nanoparticles dispersed in ink solution
[ ] Electromagnetic pumps that induce a current in a liquid metal 
[ ] Wax-metal composites
[x] All of the above
[explanation]
Metal jetting can be performed by using nanoparticles dispersed in ink solution as done by XJet, through the use of electromagnetic pumps if the metal can be handled in liquid form as done by Vader Systems, and by using wax-metal composites in solder paste dispensing applications.
[explanation]

name: Question #3
markdown:
>>In the use of magnetohydrodynamics to eject liquid metal, what is the purpose of the electromagnet?||Select all that apply.<<
[x] Induce a current in the liquid metal
[x] Create a magnetic field
[ ] Induce a magnetic field in the liquid metal
[ ] All of the above
[explanation]
The purpose of the electromagnet in MHD is to create a magnetic field and to induce a current in the liquid metal, the combination of these two creates a force that ejects droplets of metal.
[explanation]
